## Migration Analysis

Your code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern with `Thread.Abort`. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException`. Here's the full migration:

### Pattern Inventory

| API Found | Issue | Replacement |
|-----------|-------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` / SYSLIB0006 | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in .NET 8 | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

---

### ✅ Migrated Code (Preferred — Cooperative Cancellation)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate MUST check the token for cancellation to be effective.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

**Caller migration:**

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ComputeResult(), timeout);

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must cooperate with the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return finalResult;
}, timeout);
```

---

### ⚠️ Alternative: Fire-and-Forget (When Work Can't Accept a Token)

If you have unmodifiable work (e.g., third-party code), the background task **will keep running** after timeout — this is a fundamental difference from `Thread.Abort`:

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Runs work with a timeout. WARNING: if the work doesn't cooperate,
    /// it continues running in the background after timeout.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var task = Task.Run(work);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            cts.Cancel();
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation is not immediate** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints (`ThrowIfCancellationRequested`). CPU-bound work without checkpoints won't stop. |
| **Leaked background work** | The fire-and-forget variant lets orphaned work keep running. Prefer the cooperative version. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. Always `using`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard distinguishes timeout from external cancellation. |
| **`default(T)` nullability** | `T result = default` may produce a nullable warning in .NET 8 with NRTs enabled. The task-based approach avoids this entirely. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If you absolutely must hard-kill unmodifiable work, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` — that's the only .NET 8 equivalent of forced termination. |

The cooperative (`Func<CancellationToken, T>`) version is strongly recommended. It makes the contract explicit: the work **must** check the token.
